SIMPLE: indulgence
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indulgence
<hw>In*dul"gence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>indulgentia</ets>: cf. F. <ets>indulgence</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of indulging or humoring; the quality of
being indulgent; forbearance of restrain or control.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If I were a judge, that word <qex>indulgence</qex> should never
issue from my lips.</q> <rj><qau>Tooke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They err, that through <qex>indulgence</qex> to others, or
fondness to any sin in themselves, substitute for repentance anything
less.</q> <rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An indulgent act; favor granted;
gratification.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If all these gracious <qex>indulgences</qex> are without any
effect on us, we must perish in our own folly.</q>
<rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>Remission of the temporal
punishment due to sins, after the guilt of sin has been remitted by
sincere repentance; absolution from the censures and public penances of
the church. It is a payment of the debt of justice to God by the
application of the merits of Christ and his saints to the contrite soul
through the church. It is therefore believed to diminish or destroy for
sins the punishment of purgatory.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indulgence</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Indulgence
<hw>In*dul"gence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To grant an
indulgence to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indulgency</ent>⟦br⟧
